    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-02T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-02T07:00:00-05:00" n="833"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d833">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">681.003/144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-02T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 2, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 2—8:37 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. Embassy’s telegram 31, January 26, noon, and despatch number 941, January
                        31st.<note n="41" xml:id="d833fn41">Despatch not printed.</note> Director of
                    African Division informs member of Embassy that French official who was
                    discussing here the question <pb facs="1067" n="965" xml:id="pg_965"/> relating
                    to the customs regime in Morocco has returned to Paris after having reached a
                    tentative agreement with the Italian authorities on the subject of the
                    establishment of a system of quotas on certain importations into Morocco as well
                    as on the augmentation of customs duties up to 25 per cent on certain
                    commodities.</p>
                <p>The Italian authorities state that they have insisted that the principles
                    underlying the customs regime in Morocco must be maintained and that any
                    arrangements of a practical nature such as outlined above must be agreed to by
                    all the interested governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
